  "prompt": "How is the formula for average acceleration determined?",
  "response": "The formula for average acceleration is determined by calculating the change in velocity over a specific time interval. Here's a detailed breakdown:\n\n1. Formula:\nAverage Acceleration = (Change in Velocity) \u00f7 (Change in Time)\na(avg) = \u0394v \u00f7 \u0394t\n\n2. Components:\n- \u0394v represents the change in velocity (final velocity - initial velocity)\n- \u0394t represents the change in time\n- a(avg) represents average acceleration\n\n3. Derivation steps:\n- Start with the definition of acceleration as rate of change of velocity\n- Use basic calculus principles of change in velocity over time\n- Simplify to create the fundamental average acceleration equation\n\n4. Units:\n- Velocity change is typically in meters/second (m/s)\n- Time change is in seconds (s)\n- Resulting average acceleration is in meters/second squared (m/s\u00b2)\n\n5. Important considerations:\n- Represents the overall velocity change during a specific time period\n- Does not capture instantaneous acceleration\n- Can be positive, negative, or zero depending on velocity changes\n\nThis formula provides a straightforward method to calculate average acceleration in various physical scenarios.",
